{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636591"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17590"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17590"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10304"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71424"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10304"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10061"},{"type":"tags","id":"10080"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24105"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71424"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPyruvate is a crucial metabolic intermediate that sits at the intersection of several important biochemical pathways. It is produced during the final step of glycolysis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation of pyruvate during glycolysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conversion of malate to pyruvate via malic enzyme","Conversion of lactate to pyruvate with NAD+ reduction","Conversion of alanine to pyruvate via oxidative deamination","Conversion of acetyl-CoA to pyruvate via pyruvate dehydrogenase","Conversion of phosphoenolpyruvate to pyruvate with ATP generation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econversion of phosphoenolpyruvate to pyruvate with ATP generation\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct mechanism for pyruvate formation during glycolysis. This reaction is catalysed by pyruvate kinase and generates one ATP molecule per pyruvate molecule through substrate-level phosphorylation. Since two pyruvate molecules are formed per glucose molecule, this step generates two ATP molecules per complete cycle of glycolysis. The reaction is irreversible and represents an important regulatory point in glycolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of lactate to pyruvate with NAD+ reduction\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the reverse reaction of lactate dehydrogenase and occurs during gluconeogenesis, not glycolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of alanine to pyruvate via oxidative deamination\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a transamination reaction that occurs during amino acid catabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of malate to pyruvate via malic enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs during the malate-aspartate shuttle, not during glycolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of acetyl-CoA to pyruvate via pyruvate dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E - This reaction proceeds in the opposite direction; pyruvate dehydrogenase converts pyruvate to acetyl-CoA\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe formation of pyruvate represents the end of the glycolytic pathway, after which pyruvate can enter several metabolic pathways including the citric acid cycle, gluconeogenesis, or fermentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pyruvate is formed from phosphoenolpyruvate via pyruvate kinase in the final step of glycolysis.","The conversion of phosphoenolpyruvate to pyruvate generates one ATP molecule per pyruvate molecule formed.","This reaction is irreversible and represents a key regulatory point in glycolysis."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17590"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T15:48:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T15:50:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10304"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71424"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"